<TITLE>Chelsea make late swoop for Juventus target</TITLE>


<TEXT>
With veteran defender Branislav Ivanovic <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">heading</EVENT> closer to the Stamford Bridge exit, and skipper John Terry unlikely to be <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">rewarded</EVENT> with a new deal at the end of this season, Chelsea Manager Antonio Conte has already <EVENT eid="e3" class="ASPECTUAL">begun preparing</EVENT> for his <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="X">second</TIMEX3> season in charge of the Blues by <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">lining</EVENT> up defensive reinforcements. 
 
And to <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> matters easier for the Italian, he has <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">taken</EVENT> a peek at former club Juventus' summer shopping list and is <EVENT eid="e7" class="I_ACTION">hoping</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">beat</EVENT> them to the <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">signing</EVENT> of Schalke defender Sead Kolasinac. 
 
Kolasinac, a <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="X">23</TIMEX3> year old Bosnian defender, is out of contract at Schalke in the summer, and Juventus were <EVENT eid="e10" class="I_ACTION">hoping</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e11" class="I_ACTION">sign</EVENT> the player on a free transfer having <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">come</EVENT> to a verbal agreement with the youngster. 
 
Conte though is <EVENT eid="e13" class="I_STATE">believed</EVENT> to be <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">hijacking</EVENT> the deal by <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">tabling</EVENT> an <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">offer</EVENT> in excess of 4 million, <EVENT eid="e17" class="I_STATE">hoping</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">convince</EVENT> the German club to <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">sell</EVENT> him <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3> rather than risk <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">losing</EVENT> him for free in the <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="2017-SU">summer</TIMEX3>. 
 
With Schalke having had previous experiences of doing similar business with Tottenham with regards to the transfer of Lewis Holtby some seasons back, they will in all likelihood jump at the possibility of making some money on the young <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">left</EVENT> back, and in exchange Chelsea can <EVENT eid="e22" class="I_STATE">look</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">integrate</EVENT> the player into their first team this season itself, with the youngster quite possibly <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">playing</EVENT> a useful role in the title run-in. 
 
{fcomment id=61498}
</TEXT>


